3":"before 1033","1033":"1033","1032":"1032","abt 970":"about 0970","980":"0980","0950":"0950","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","0990":"0990","1057":"1057","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","about 1032":"about 1032","about 1033":"about 1033","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","Moray, Dalriada, Albia, (Scotlandireland)":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"mac","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Cuong, Minh, Lien, Muoi, Thanh, Tho, Tieu, Vinh, Anh, Beo, Binh, Chau.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 麥 (see   Mai   2) and 莫 (see   Mo   1).","Vietnamese (<b>Mạc</b>): from Chinese 莫 ‘nothing; nonexistent’; see   Mo   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Mai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Hoa, Son, Dung, Long, Binh, Minh, Thu, Hue, Huong, Thuy.  Chinese Chi, Hong, Ho, Sang, Han, Hang, Jian, Li, Man, Mei, Sen, Wei.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 麥, meaning ‘wheat’ in Chinese: (i) from Mai Qiu (麥丘), the title of a man in the state of Qi (located mainly in present-day Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), who, despite being very old, came to celebrate the birthday of the Duke Huan of Qi (ruler of the state of Qi, died 643  BC ). His descendants inherited 麥, the first part of his title, as their surname. (ii) borne by descendants of Mai Tie Zhang (麥鐵杖), a famous general during the Sui dynasty (581–618  AD ). His descendants were scattered around southern China.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 買, meaning ‘buy’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of the king Song Weizi, founder of the state of Song. (ii) borne by descendants of the Duke Dao of Xu (ruler of the state of Xu, 546–523  BC ), possibly inheriting his personal name. (iii) from the first element of the personal name Mai Zhu Chu (買朱鉏), style name of an official who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) it has also been traced back to other ethnic groups in northern China."]}]},{"name":"Máil","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Scottish:  see  Meil  .   Black  , at Meal, notes that the surname may not have originated in Shetland but derive from the settlement of some Orkney families there in the early 17th century.","2  Welsh, English:  see  Male  .","3  Irish:  see  Malley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Malley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Malley  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in northern France called Mailly (Marne, Somme, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Mlej</b> (see   Malay  )."]},{"name":"Male","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Mael</i> (literally ‘prince’).","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>mail</i> ‘mallet, club, mace’, or Middle English (Old French) <i>maille</i> ‘ring (of chain mail), armour’, or Old French <i>maille</i> ‘speckle, stain’, or Middle English <i>maille</i> (Old French <i>maaille</i>) ‘coin worth half a penny’, or from a shortened form of Anglo-Norman French <i>amel</i>, Old French <i>esma(i)l</i> ‘enamel’ (compare   Mailer  ). Any of these terms might have been used to characterize an individual's behaviour, occupation, or appearance.","English: nickname Middle English (Old French) <i>male</i> ‘bag, pouch’, also ‘stomach, belly’, perhaps given to someone who wore a distinctive pouch or bag or who made such bags (compare the Middle English occupational term <i>malemakere</i>), or to someone with a prominent belly."]},{"name":"Black","meanings":["English and Scottish: chiefly from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>, <i>blaca</i>), a nickname given from the earliest times to a swarthy or dark-haired man. However, Middle English <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."]},{"name":"Meil","meanings":["Scottish (Orkney): habitational name from one of several places in Orkney (and perhaps Shetland) named from Old Norse <i>melr</i> ‘sandbank’. The surname is now spelled <i>Meil</i> in Orkney and <b>Mail</b> in Shetland. The name is rare in Britain and Ireland.","German: variant of   Meile  ."]}]},{"name":"Gille","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Aegidus</i>, Old French <i>Gide</i>.  See  <b>Giles</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gille Coemgáin mac Máil Brigti Mormaer of Moray was born about 0970, in Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Máil Brigti mac Ruaidrí Mormaer of Moray, was 21 and his mother, N N Mail Brigti, was 21. He married Lady Gruoch mi Boedhe Queen of Scots about 1032. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1033, in Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland, at the age of 64, and was buried in Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"abt 970–1033":"umbes 0970–1033","0970–1033":"0970–1033","1013–1057":"1013–1057","1033–1058":"1033–1058","0950–0990":"0950–0990","0950–0980":"0950–0980","before 1033":"enne 1033","1033":"1033","1032":"1032","abt 970":"umbes 0970","980":"0980","0950":"0950","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","0990":"0990","1057":"1057","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","about 1032":"umbes 1032","about 1033":"umbes 1033","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Moray, Dalriada, Albia, (Scotlandireland)":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland"},"fi":{"abt 970–1033":"noin 0970–1033","0970–1033":"0970–1033","1013–1057":"1013–1057","1033–1058":"1033–1058","0950–0990":"0950–0990","0950–0980":"0950–0980","before 1033":"ennen vuotta 1033","1033":"1033","1032":"1032","abt 970":"noin 0970","980":"0980","0950":"0950","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","0990":"0990","1057":"1057","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","about 1032":"noin 1032","about 1033":"noin 1033","Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Moray, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Moray, Dalriada, Albia, (Scotlandireland)":"Moray, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland"},"fr":{"abt 970–1033":"environ 0970–1033","0970–1033":"0970–1033","1013–1057":"1013–1057","1033–1058":"1033–1058","0950–0990":"0950–0990","0950–0980":"0950–0980","before 1033":"avant 1033","1033":"1033","1032":"1032","abt 970":"environ 0970","980":"0980","0950":"0950","0970":